article.description:
Jamie Redd came off the injured list at just the
right time for the Seattle Storm.
article.headline: Redd scores all 13 of her points in second half
article.linkText: Redd's second-half outburst leads Storm to win
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Jamie Redd came off the injured list at just the right time for the Seattle Storm. Hours after being activated, Redd noticed that her teammates looked a little sluggish and she was determined to add some second-half energy. Redd scored all of her 13 points in the second half to lead the Storm to another comeback win as they beat the Charlotte Sting 65-59 on Thursday night. "It is an awesome, incredible feeling,'' Redd said. "I've always been the type of person that even if I do get hurt I don't let it slow me down. For me, it was just about bringing high energy.'' Redd, who had been out with a knee injury, played 13 minutes as a reserve in her first game of the season and helped Seattle to its franchise-best winning streak of three games. The Storm beat the Minnesota Lynx in overtime Tuesday. "Jamie Red-Hot Redd!'' coach Lin Dunn said. "Obviously she overcame her hurt knee and strained foot. She stayed positive and was ready to play. ... Jamie's a scorer and is going to find a way to score.'' Sue Bird had 17 points and seven assists for the Storm (3-1), including a 3-pointer with 6:50 left that broke a 46-all tie. Then the Sting turned the ball over and Bird jumped into the air and threw up her fist in excitement. "Jamie Redd triggered it,'' Bird said of the comeback. "Anytime someone comes in and gives you that kind of lift, there's no telling what can happen.'' Reserve Tammy Sutton-Brown had a team-high 11 points and six rebounds for the Sting (2-1), who opened the season with wins over the defending champion Los Angeles Sparks and the four-time champion Houston Comets. Allison Feaster and Dawn Staley each scored 10 points for Charlotte, which shot 23.1 percent in the second half. "We can't stick with the L.A. and Houston wins too long or the next game will be affected,'' Staley said. Thursday was supposed to be the first time Bird and 6-foot-5 center Lauren Jackson played together, but Jackson was a last-minute scratch from the starting lineup and did not play because of a sprained right ankle, which also caused her to miss Seattle's first three games. She participated in the team's morning shootaround but was re-evaluated just before the game by a team doctor, who determined she still had significant swelling and bruising in her ankle. Jackson, the Storm's leading scorer last season, was the WNBA's top draft pick in 2001 and an All-Star as a rookie, while Bird was the No. 1 overall pick this year. Simone Edwards replaced Jackson and scored 12 points. After a dismal first half, the Storm pulled within 42-39 on Redd's layup with 9:45 left, then Redd tied it with two free throws at the 8:08 mark. She scored seven points over the final 4:54 and all of her points came in the last 10:42. "Jamie Redd was able to hit big shots with the shot clock going down,'' said Staley, who had six assists. "She got to the line and made some free throws. It was a good stretch for her.'' Game notes
Dunn said she may activate guard Michelle Marciniak for Sunday's game against Utah. Marciniak has an injured right ankle. ... Seattle placed forward Takeisha Lewis on the injured list to make roster room for Redd. Lewis has tendinitis in both knees. ... It was a homecoming for Charlotte rookie Sheila Lambert, who attended Seattle's Chief Sealth High School. But she is on the injured list with a broken bone in her right leg. ... Sonja Henning had a career-high eight rebounds for Seattle.
